                   SECTION 2. ALC-CMT CONFIGURATION OVERVIEW



          The ALC-CMT configuration file generates tables that, when
          assembled, are used to validate users and allocate
          resources.  This file consists of two distinct types of
          macros; those which are related to the LUD (Local User
          Directory) and those which are not.

          LUD Macros
          __________

          The LUD Macros may be looked at in terms of three discreet
          units.  These are USER, ADDRESS, and OPTIONAL.

          Together the USER macros define all information pertinent to
          the users who are valid on the ALC-CMT being configured.
          Within the USER MACRO section there is one macro
          specifically labled the User Macro.  It defines the user
          parameters for circuits to be built from the terminals to
          the ALC-CMT.  Also contained within the USER MACRO section
          is the SETMAG macro.  The SETMAG defines those circuits
          which will be built from the ALC-HIF to the ALC-CMT.

          ADDRESS Macros define all session host-addressing
          information.  Addressing can be set up for each host so that
          a specific user has a dedicated address, or so that users
          are assigned addresses on a first come, first served basis
          from a configured pool of addresses.

          Additional features can be included in the ALC-CMT through
          configuration of the various OPTIONAL macros.  These include
          such macros as Auto Sign-In and Sign-Off, Statistics
          Gathering, Security Code, LOKCHK, and Project Code.  The
          method for configuring each of these macros is detailed in
          the OPTIONAL Macros section of this manual.


          GENERAL Macros
          ______________

          The GENERAL macros are used to define the host number,
          banner message, number of bufferlets used, the 'shut/answer'
          status of the interface, and the logoff string.

          These macros must be grouped together and may be placed
          either before or after the LUD macros within the tymfile.
