          3.1.4.  The SETMAG Macro
          ________________________

          This macro defines the circuits to be built from the ALC-HIF
          to the ALC-CMT.  One SETMAG must be defined for each circuit
          to be built.

          The format of the SETMAG macro is:

               SETMAG(res number,res code,line width,reset time,screen
                         type,translation table,supplier line,support
                         printer,industry code delimiter,industry code
                         size,pointer to form specification table,size
                         of industry code field,bypass character,PNR
                         security,service type)

          where:

              res number is a decimal number expressed by a constant
              __________
                        of the form res.xy where xy is the airline res
                        code (e.g., res.tw, res.ea, etc.).

              res code is a two character code identifying the airline
              ________
                        xy in the res number defined above.)

              line width is a number specifying the maximum size of
              __________
                        one display line in the host.

              reset time is the minimum number of seconds before a
              __________
                        user can escape from a command (unlock the
                        keyboard).

              screen typ is always set to SCNPAR (an obsolete
              __________
                        parameter).

              translation table is the label of a table used to
              _________________
                        translate ALC character set (i.e.;SABRE) into
                        ASCII characters.

              supplier line is the supplier's communications line
              _____________
                        number.

              support printer specifies whether this res supports
              _______________
                        printers or not:
                    0 = doesn't support printers
                    1 = supports printers

              industry code delimiter is a delimiter character (in hex
              _______________________
                        SABRE code) optionally used in printer
                        messages to indicate the industry code field.
