
          A command group may contain any number of commands.  Each
          command in turn, may be configured to accept one or several
          responses. Optionally any command or response may be defined
          with an action to be taken when the command is sent or the
          response is received.  Currently, there is only one ACTION
          being used.  This is the 'RSPDNE' option that can be
          configured for a response macro.  Responses that are
          configured with the RSPDNE parameter indicate to the ALC-CMT
          that when this response is received the interface should
          exit the current command/response sequence and go on to the
          next sequence defined.  This can be seen by looking at
          Diagram 1.A.  If the first response configured for command 1
          is received, command 2 is not executed, but instead the ALC-
          CMT jumps down to the next Sign Command Set and executes the
          command configured in that sequence.

          Sign-In and Sign-Off macro structures are labeled either as
          SIGNIx or SIGNOx, where x may be any ASCII character or wild
          character used to identify the command group - for example,
          SIGNI1.


          SGNRES macros are used to designate whether the Auto Sign-In
          and/or Auto Sign-Off feature is supported for a specific
          service (RES), and which Sign Command Group should be used
          for that RES.


          3.3.1.1.  The SGNBEG Macro
          __________________________

          The SGNBEG macro indicates the beginning of the command/re-
          sponse sequence for the message exchange between the ALC-CMT
          and the host.  This macro must appear before the SGNCMD and
          SGNRSP macros, and it must be paired with a SGNEND macro.

          The format for the SGNBEG macro is:

               SGNBEG


















          April 22, 1987             - 17 -                   ALCC.GEN




          ALCC SYS GEN                                   3. LUD MACROS




          3.3.1.2.  The SGNCMD Macro
          __________________________

          The SGNCMD macro is used to generate the SC format command
          string(s) that ALC-CMT will send to the host.  Multiple
          command strings may be configured per RES or per Sign
          Command Group.  Each command must be coupled with at least
          one response, although several responses may be configured
          per command.

          The format of the SGNCMD macro is:

               SGNCMD(cmd,action)

          where:

               cmd       is the SC string which will be sent by the
               ___
                         ALC-CMT to the host.  This field may consist
                         of up to 255 ASCII characters.

               action    represents an action which is to be taken
               ______
                         before the command sequence is sent to the
                         host.  It is an optional parameter and when
                         it is not used, there is no action to be
                         performed for the command being defined.




          3.3.1.3.  The SGNRSP Macro
          __________________________

          This macro represents the configured response which the ALC-
          CMT expects to receive from the host.  At least one response
          per host command must be configured but multiple responses
          may be configured for any one command.  Therefore this macro
          may repeat itself after a SGNCMD macro.

          The format of the SGNRSP macro is:

               SGNRSP(rsp,action)

          where:

               rsp       is the response expected for the command
               ___
                         configured in the SGNCMD macro.  There may be
                         several responses to one command.  This field
                         may consist of up to 255 ASCII characters
                         including wild characters.  (Wild characters
                         are represented with the pound sign '#'.)

               action    represents an action to be taken when this
               ______
                         response is received.  Currently the only
                         type of action being used is RSPDNE.  When a
                         response is received for which the RSPDNE



          April 22, 1987             - 18 -                   ALCC.GEN




          ALCC SYS GEN                                   3. LUD MACROS




                         option is defined, the ALC-CMT will jump to
                         the next Command Set, without issuing any
                         other commands in the current Command Set.
                         When no action parameter is defined, the next
                         command in the current Command Set is
                         performed.




          3.3.1.4.  The SGNEND Macro
          __________________________

          This macro is always paired with the SGNBEG macro.  It is
          used to end a Command Set or a Sign Command Group.  When
          this macro is used to end a Command Set, it is defined with
          the parameter ENDSET.  When it is used to end a Sign Command
          Group, the parameter ENDGRP must be defined.

          The format for this macro is:

               SGNEND(ENDSET) or SGNEND (ENDGRP)

          where:

               ENDGRP    indicates that the end of a Sign Command
               ______
                         Group has been reached.

               ENDSET    indicates that the end of a Command Set has
               ______
                         been reached.




          3.3.1.5.  The SGNRES Macro
          __________________________

          This macro designates whether Auto Sign-In and/or Auto Sign-
          Off are supported for a particular RES, and indicates which
          Auto Sign-In or Sign-Off Sign Command Group to use for that
          RES.  This macro is used only for interfaces that support
          the Auto Sign-In or Off features.

          The format for this macro is:

               SGNRES(RES_NUM,Auto Sign-In ptr,Auto Sign-Off ptr)

          where:

               RES NUM    is the RES number
               _______

               Auto Sign-In ptr is the label SIGNIx, with x
               ________________
                         identifying which Auto Sign-In Command Group
                         to use for this RES.  This parameter should
                         be omitted to configure a RES without Auto
                         Sign-In capability.


          April 22, 1987             - 19 -                   ALCC.GEN




          ALCC SYS GEN                                   3. LUD MACROS




               Auto Sign-off ptr  is the label SIGNOx, with x
               _________________
                         identifying which Auto Sign-Off Command Group
                         to use for this RES.  This parameter should
                         be omitted to configure a RES without Auto
                         Sign-Off capability.




          3.3.1.6.  Configurable Retry Parameters
          _______________________________________

          The retry attempts that the ALC-CMT makes in signing in or
          off a host are set up with predefined default values which
          may be changed when necessary.  This section defines each of
          these parameters and includes a description of how to change
          them.

          The following parameters may be defined anywhere within the
          tymfile but for the sake of clarity and easy reference it is
          best to place them immediately following the Sign-In and
          Sign-Off macros.   Each of the parameters shown is listed
          with its current default value.  The parameters are defined
          acccording to the following formulas:

                         DEFDEF(VARIABLE NAME,$A VALUE)

                      DEFDEF(VARIABLE NAME,$A RATE*VALUE)

          where:

               DEFDEF assignes a numeric value to the variable
               ______

               VARIABLE NAME is a six letter name for the variable
               _____________

               $A means that the variable value shall be represented
               __
                  in decimal

               RATE is equivilent to 600 FASTC ticks or 1 second
               ____

               VALUE is the numeric value of the variable
               _____














