          3.3.3.  SECURITY CODE MACROS
          ____________________________

          SECURITY CODE macros are used by ALC-CMT as an added sec-
          curity measure for message transmission.  This feature was
          originally designed for the Airline Reservation systems
          which required high security for PNRs, but it can be used
          for any type of message.

          When this feature is in effect, the ALC-CMT checks all
          messages for industry code number.  This number is then
          compared with the numbers in the configured Security pool.
          If there is a match, the message is transmitted to the user.
          If there is not a match, then it is discarded.

          More than one pool can be defined, and these pools can be
          shared by several users.


          3.3.3.1.  The BEGICP Macro
          __________________________

          This macro starts the beginning of a particular pool of in-
          dustry code numbers.  BEGICP Has no parameters.


          3.3.3.2.  The INCODE Macro
          __________________________

          This macro  specifies one industry code number for a par-
          ticular pool.  There can be more than one INCODE call pool.

          The format of the INCODE macro is:

               INCODE(industry code number)

          where:

               industry code number is the industry code number in the
               ____________________
                         form of a string.


          3.3.3.3.  The ENCICP Macro
          __________________________

          This macro ends a particular pool of industry code numbers.
          ENDICP Has no parameters.













          April 22, 1987             - 23 -                   ALCC.GEN




          ALCC SYS GEN                                   3. LUD MACROS




          3.3.4.  The LOKCHK Macro
          ________________________

          The LOKCHK  macro enables  or disables  data flow  in either
          direction.
          If this macro is not used within a configuration then the
          default value for it will be 'OFF' in each direction,
          meaning that no restrictions will be placed on data flow.

          The format of the LOKCHK macro is:

               LOKCHK(USR,HST)

          where:

               usr is the option (ON or OFF) defined for the user
               ___
                      keyboard.

               ON  means the keyboard will be locked for the user,
               that is the user cannot type more than one command.

               OFF  means the keyboard will not be locked for the
               user, that is the user can type a command followed by
               carriage return, then type subsequent commands.


               hst is the option (ON or OFF) defined for the host.
               ___

               ON  means the host cannot send data to the user when
               the user is in input mode, that is it can only send one
               response per user command.

               OFF  means the host can send data to the user when the
               user is in input mode, that is it can send more than
               one response per user command.


