

          4.2.  THE NMBFLT MACRO
          ______________________

          This macro defines the number of bufferlets to be used.

          The format for this macro is:

               NMBFLT(# bufferlets)

          where:

               #bufferlets is the decimal number of bufferlets to be
               ___________
                         allocated.  Each bufferlet has six data
                         characters and two bytes of link.




          4.3.  THE SHTANS MACRO
          ______________________

          This macro defines the soft shut and answered levels.

          The format for this macro is:

               SHTANS(# ports for shut,# ports for answer)

          where:

               # ports for shut is the decimal number of ports to be
               ________________
                         left in the available pool in order for the
                         ALC-CMT to shut itself.  This 'shut' occurs
                         if there are the configured number of ports
                         or fewer available.



          April 22, 1987             - 27 -                   ALCC.GEN




          ALCC SYS GEN                               4. GENERAL MACROS




               #ports for answer is the decimal number of ports to be
               _________________
                         left in the available pool in order for the
                         ALC-CMT to answer.  This number should be
                         larger than the number configured for 'shut'.






          4.4.  THE MAKBAN MACRO
          ______________________

          This macro defines the banner string.  It has only one
          parameter, that of the banner message to be displayed to the
          user upon logging in.  The banner string may contain any
          number of characters up to the length of one entire screen,
          although most banners will require only one or two lines.
          Depending on the type of terminal used, banner data may or
          may not wrap when the end of a line (80 characters) is
          reached.  Therefore, it is prudent to define a carriage
          return and linefeed after each 79th character of data
          entered in the banner string.

          The format for this macro is:

               MAKBAN(banner string)

          where:

               banner string is the data string which will be dis-
               _____________
                         played to the user upon login.  Control
                         characters such as carriage return or line
                         feed can be defined by inserting a double
                         quote followed by two hex digits for the
                         ASCII code of the character.  The quote will
                         not be displayed.

               For example, given that "8D equals a carriage return,
                         and "8A is a linefeed; with the banner string
                         'Welcome to the ALC-CMT "8D"8A, the user will
                         see 'Welcome to the ALC-CMT' followed by a
                         carriage return and a linefeed.

